The expected value \( E(Z) \) is computed as follows. The lifetimes \( X_1 \) and \( X_2 \) are independent and identically distributed exponential random variables with mean \( \theta = 2 \), so the rate parameter is \( \lambda = 1/2 \).

Define \( Y_1 = \min(X_1, X_2) \) and \( Y_2 = \max(X_1, X_2) \). The cost is \( Z = 2Y_1 + Y_2 \), so \( E(Z) = 2E(Y_1) + E(Y_2) \).

- The minimum of two independent exponential random variables with rate \( \lambda \) is exponential with rate \( 2\lambda \). Thus, \( E(Y_1) = 1/(2\lambda) \).
- The maximum \( Y_2 \) satisfies \( E(Y_2) = E(Y_1) + 1/\lambda \) due to the memoryless property, so \( E(Y_2) = 1/(2\lambda) + 1/\lambda = 3/(2\lambda) \).

Substituting \( \lambda = 1/2 \):
- \( E(Y_1) = 1/(2 \times 1/2) = 1/1 = 1 \),
- \( E(Y_2) = 3/(2 \times 1/2) = 3/1 = 3 \).

Therefore, \( E(Z) = 2 \times 1 + 3 = 5 \).

Alternatively, \( Z = Y_1 + X_1 + X_2 \), and \( E(Z) = E(Y_1) + E(X_1) + E(X_2) = 1 + 2 + 2 = 5 \), confirming the result.

