Solution: The ground-state energy of positronium is calculated based on the reduced mass of the electron-positron system. Since both particles have the same mass, the reduced mass is half the electron mass. The ground-state energy of hydrogen is -13.6 eV, and for positronium, the energy is half of this value due to the reduced mass effect. Therefore, the ground-state energy of positronium is -6.8 eV.

